Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: The existing work on stroke-based representation of Chinese characters, such as StrokeNet, has demonstrated that decomposing characters into Latinized stroke sequences can alleviate parameter and learning bottlenecks in NMT. However, these approaches treat stroke sequences as linear strings processed by sequence models, thereby neglecting higher-level structural semantics—such as radical composition, hierarchical topology, and spatial configuration—that are cognitively and linguistically significant in how humans interpret Chinese characters. While Paper 2 introduces graph-based modeling to capture stroke order dynamics, it does not integrate symbolic linguistic rules with neural learning for structured representation. Moreover, none of the current methods explicitly align stroke sequences with subword tokenization mechanisms (e.g., BPE, Unigram) used in modern NMT systems, limiting their compatibility and generalization. My intuition is that a hybrid neuro-symbolic approach—one that combines the discrete, rule-based structure of stroke-rules and radical decomposition with end-to-end learnable neural representations—can yield more interpretable, efficient, and linguistically grounded character encodings. By designing a system that generates Latinized stroke sequences enriched with structural annotations (e.g., branching points, component boundaries), we can enable subword models to split and compose tokens based not just on frequency but on morpho-visual regularities. This would allow NMT systems to better generalize across rare or unseen characters while preserving semantic transparency. Unlike prior art, this idea integrates symbolic knowledge (e.g., official stroke order standards, radical dictionaries) directly into the sequence generation pipeline, creating a *structure-aware*, *computationally lightweight*, and *subword-compatible* representation. It also opens new avenues for data augmentation via controlled stroke perturbation and radical swapping within the Latinized space.

