  "Idea": "We propose a novel framework called Hybrid Neuro-Symbolic Latinized Stroke Sequence Representation (HNLSR) for structure-aware subword modeling in Neural Machine Translation (NMT) of Chinese. The core idea is to transform each Chinese character into an enriched Latinized stroke sequence that explicitly encodes both temporal stroke order and hierarchical structural information through symbolic annotations derived from linguistic priors (e.g., Kangxi radicals, GB stroke classification). Unlike StrokeNet, which maps strokes to letters in a flat sequence (e.g., 'ajaie' for 凹), HNLSR augments the base stroke string with delimiters and tags indicating radical boundaries, stroke grouping, and topological relations (e.g., 'r1[s3s4]_s5' where 'r1' denotes a primary radical and brackets indicate subcomponents). These annotated sequences are then fed into a dual-path encoder: one symbolic rule matcher that parses structural patterns using finite-state transducers, and one neural transformer-based subword model that learns distributed representations. The two streams are fused via cross-attention, enabling the model to benefit from both hard linguistic constraints and soft statistical learning. This hybrid design allows subword segmentation algorithms (like BPE) to operate over semantically meaningful units rather than purely frequency-driven splits, improving generalization on low-frequency characters and enhancing zero-shot transfer. For example, when encountering a rare character composed of known radicals and stroke patterns, the symbolic path can activate plausible decompositions even if the full character is absent from training data. Furthermore, we introduce a stroke-to-Latin mapping function grounded in the Standardized Chinese Stroke Order Rules (GB/T 16159-2012), ensuring consistency and cross-dataset compatibility. We also develop a stroke-level data augmentation method—StrokeDrop and RadicalSwap—that operates directly in the Latinized space by randomly m