Both Idea 0 (HNLSR) and Idea 1 (GASLE) propose innovative extensions to StrokeNet by enriching Latinized stroke sequences with structural information for use in NMT. However, when evaluating novelty against the provided literature, a critical distinction emerges.

Paper 2 introduces StrokeNet, which maps Chinese characters to flat Latinized stroke sequences (e.g., "ajaie") without structural or spatial annotations—this is the baseline both ideas aim to improve upon. Paper 1 discusses graph-based modeling of stroke order and compositional structure, indicating prior exploration of structural and temporal character decomposition. Papers 3 and 5 explore visual/glyph-based representations using CNNs and pre-training, showing that visual form and internal character structure have been investigated, though not through Latinized sequences.

Idea 0 (HNLSR) enhances StrokeNet by adding symbolic delimiters and radical tags (e.g., 'r1[s3s4]_s5') to encode hierarchical structure, processed via a hybrid neuro-symbolic architecture. While this is an intelligent integration of linguistic priors into subword modeling, similar symbolic augmentation strategies—especially radical-based decomposition and rule-based tagging—have conceptual parallels in existing work on radical-aware models and graph-based representations (e.g., Paper 1, Paper 5). The use of finite-state transducers with neural models is also explored in other NLP domains, reducing its relative novelty.

In contrast, Idea 1 (GASLE) introduces a fundamentally new dimension: **geometric awareness via directional operators learned from handwriting dynamics**. Instead of relying on hard-coded symbolic boundaries, GASLE encodes spatial transitions (→, ↓, ⊂, etc.) derived from real stroke trajectories using a differentiable module (DSPM), and integrates them into attention mechanisms (GASA) as geometric biases. This approach bridges continuous spatial reasoning with discrete symbolic representation in a Latin-compatible format—an idea not present in any of the cited papers. Moreover, MorphoAugment techniques like Mirror Perturbation and Vectorial Radical Swap operate on geometric similarity, going beyond StrokeNet-style augmentations. The Geometry-Aware Self-Attention mechanism is also novel, modulating attention based on predicted spatial proximity rather than just token co-occurrence.

Crucially, while HNLSR builds on known symbolic decomposition (radicals + rules), GASLE introduces a **learned, geometrically grounded, yet interpretable extension of Latinized strokes**, which represents a more significant departure from StrokeNet and existing glyph/structure-aware models. It uniquely combines differentiable geometric modeling, handwriting dynamics, and subword compatibility in a way that has not been explored in the provided literature.

Therefore, despite both ideas being strong, **Idea 1 (GASLE)** demonstrates higher novelty due to its original integration of directional geometry into the Latinized stroke framework, enabling spatially informed, morphology-aware NMT with new architectural and augmentation innovations.

